    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-06T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-06T17:00:00-05:00" n="781"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d781">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6359 Antimony/13: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-06T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 6, 1935—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>37. Your 56, February 1, 7 p.m., in regard to antimony monopoly.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Basing its views upon such information as is now available the Department
                        does not agree with the contentions of the Foreign Office <pb facs="0884"
                            n="772" xml:id="pg_772"/> that the treaty provisions cited in the first
                        paragraph of your telegram under reference are not applicable to the Hunan
                        Antimony Syndicate.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Department suggests that you follow the course of action outlined in the
                        concluding paragraph of your telegram under reference and that in so doing
                        you bear in mind paragraph 1 of the Department’s telegram No. 44, February
                        19, [1934,] 1 p.m.,<note n="56" xml:id="d781fn56">
                            <p>Not printed; paragraph 1 stated: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“The Department is of the opinion (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)
                                        that article 3 of the Nine Power Treaty does not preclude a
                                        protest against the establishment of a government trade
                                        monopoly; (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) that article 15 of the
                                        Sino-American Treaty of 1844 and article 14 of the
                                        Sino-French Treaty of 1858 in effect prohibit Chinese
                                        private and government as well as foreign trade monopolies
                                        and thus afford ample ground for a further protest to the
                                        Chinese Government.” (893.6359 Wolfram Ore/30)</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                        </note> in regard to the then proposed wolfram ore monopoly.<note n="57"
                            xml:id="d781fn57">For other correspondence on the wolfram monopoly, see
                                <ref target="frus1933v03#pg_593">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1933, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp. 593</ref> ff.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Has the Japanese Legation taken action in addition to that stated in the
                        first paragraph of your 578 of December 15, 4 p.m.?<note n="58"
                            xml:id="d781fn58">Not printed.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
